function RENDER {
    print("<!doctype html><html lang='en'><head><meta name='viewport' content='width=device-width,initial-scale=1'><title>Capy Language Reference</title><link rel='stylesheet' href='style.css'></head><body><div class='shell'><header class='top'><strong><a href='index.capy'>Capy Reference</a></strong><span>direct-to-Wasm language for Bearer</span></header><div class='layout'><nav aria-label='Reference chapters'><a class='active' aria-current='page' href='index.capy'>Overview</a><a href='syntax.capy'>Syntax</a><a href='types.capy'>Types & overloads</a><a href='ownership.capy'>ARC ownership</a><a href='interop.capy'>Bearer interop</a><a href='status.capy'>Implementation status</a></nav><main><section class='hero'><span class='badge'>c17 / w10</span><h1>Capy language reference</h1><p>Capy is a statically compiled, expression-oriented language that emits WebAssembly directly. Bearer discovers, compiles, publishes, and executes <code>.capy</code> units beside existing C++ <code>.uce</code> units.</p></section><h2>Reference chapters</h2><div class='grid'><a class='card' href='syntax.capy'><b>Syntax</b><span>Expression slots, functions, variables, control flow, arrays, tuples, and structs.</span></a><a class='card' href='types.capy'><b>Types and overloads</b><span>Primitive and managed types, exact overloads, compile-time any, x::type, and casts.</span></a><a class='card' href='ownership.capy'><b>ARC ownership</b><span>Borrowed parameters, owned results, cleanup edges, aggregate drop glue, and trap containment.</span></a><a class='card' href='interop.capy'><b>Bearer interoperability</b><span>Handlers, components, unit dispatch, copied BRRB2 dval values, and mixed-language boundaries.</span></a><a class='card' href='/doc/index.uce'><b>Bearer C++ API</b><span>Open the original runtime API reference for C++ units and host functions.</span></a></div><h2>Hello, Bearer</h2><pre>function RENDER {
    print(\"Hello from Capy\")
}</pre><p>Save this as <code>hello.capy</code> and request it like any other Bearer unit.</p><div class='note'>This site is itself rendered entirely by Capy units. It distinguishes implemented behavior from planned language work.</div></main></div></div></body></html>")
}
